'''Gilbert Rwabigwi''' (born 6 January 1990) is a Rwandan [[social entrepreneur]] and [http://www.rwabigwi.com blogger], who is passionate about [[literacy]], [[education]] and [[social media]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/rwabigwi|title=Rwabigwi (@Rwabigwi) {{!}} Twitter|website=www.twitter.com|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref> He is the founder<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.youli.org.rw/faq|title=F.A.Q.|website=YouLI|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref> of Youth Literacy Organisation (YouLI), a non-profit NGO whose mission is to advance literacy and [[learning]] in [[Rwanda]], especially among youth between the ages of 15 and 30. Rwabigwi is also a founding partner in [http://www.ejo.co.rw Ejo Group], a social enterprise that specialises in social media and digital [[content marketing]].

== Writing and Influence ==
Rwabigwi is a regular writer and editor at the Kigalian, an online [[magazine]] that publishes articles about trends on social media, technology, arts and culture, photography, and commentaries about [[Rwanda]]. He is also among top Rwandan influencers on Twitter and speaks at several events on issues about education, literacy, social media and culture. Since 2016, Rwabigwi is a judge in Miss Rwanda.

== Birth and Parents ==
Gilbert was born in [[Kigali]]. His father, Fulgence Bukaka, and mother, Alphonsine Mukahigiro, were killed during the [[Rwandan Genocide]] in 1994.

== Education and Activism ==
Rwabigwi was raised in Kigali, with his brothers and sisters; went to Camp Kigali Primary School and Ecole Primaire l'Horizon for his primary education. He went to [[Groupe Scolaire Officiel de Butare]] (GSOB), then Groupe Scolaire Kigombe (GSK) for his secondary education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newtimes.co.rw/section/article/2011-10-21/98651/|title=Interview: David Gilbert Rwabigwi and why he is one of Rwanda's promising authors|last=Iribagiza|first=Gloria A.|website=The New Times Rwanda|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref> Gilbert studied at the School of [[Journalism]] and [[Communication]], [[National University of Rwanda]] (NUR).

He holds a self-proclaimed PhD in [[autodidacticism]] and is one of the most respected advocates for writing<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newtimes.co.rw/section/article/2016-06-05/200491/|title=Rwabigwi on why literacy amongst youth is significant|last=Kantengwa|first=Sharon|newspaper=The New Times Rwanda|access-date=2017-01-10}}</ref> in Rwanda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theservicemag.com/index.php/en/feats-3/youth-talk/330-rwabigwi|title=Rwabigwi|last=simon|website=www.theservicemag.com|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref> He is the author of "Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow: A Collection of Poems on Genocide<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/book/yesterday-today-and-tomorrow/id845255595|title=Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow by Gilbert Rwabigwi on iBooks|website=iBooks|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref>", first published in 2008. In 2011, he was featured on the top of a list of top 10 most important Rwandan artists to know.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archived.thisisafrica.me/music/detail/2023/10-rwandan-artists-you-should-know|title=10 Rwandan Artists You Should Know - Music - This Is Africa|website=archived.thisisafrica.me|access-date=2016-04-16}}</ref>

