{{use dmy dates|date=April 2013}} {{Infobox person |name = Tevfik Esenç |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_name = |birth_date = 1904 |birth_place = |death_date = 7 October {{death year and age|1992|1904}} |death_place = |residence = [[Hacı Osman]], [[Balıkesir]], [[Turkey]] |nationality = Turkish |alma_mater = |occupation = |years_active = |net_worth = |boards = |religion = |spouse = |children = |parents = |signature = |website = }}
'''Tevfik Esenç''' (1904 – 7 October 1992) was a [[Circassians|Circassian]] exile in [[Turkey]] and the last known fully competent speaker of the [[Ubykh language]].
==Biography== Esenç was raised by his Ubykh-speaking grandparents for a time in the village of [[Hacı Osman]] in Turkey, and he served a term as the ''muhtar'' (mayor) of that village, before receiving a post in the [[civil service]] of [[Istanbul]]. There, he was able to do a great deal of work with the [[France|French]] [[linguistics|linguist]] [[Georges Dumézil]] and his associate [[Georges Charachidzé]] to help record his language.<ref name=TECW>[https://circassianworld.wordpress.com/2013/09/04/tevfik-esenc-the-last-person-able-to-speak-the-ubykh-language/ Tevfik Esenç's page in Circassian World]</ref> Not all the writings of Charachidzé (1930-2010) have been published. Others who met Esenç and produced work on Ubykh are: the Norwegian Hans Vogt (1911–92) (see his ‘[http://apsnyteka.org/file/Vogt_Dictionnaire_de_la_langue_Oubykh.pdf Dictionnaire de la Langue Oubykh]’, 1963, Universitetsvorlaget); the British [http://georgehewitt.net George Hewitt], who in [http://georgehewitt.net/articles/miscellaneous/288-turkey-summer-of-1974 1974 visited] Hacı Osman Köyü and made recordings with Esenç in Istanbul ([http://georgehewitt.net/multimedia/recordings/281-george-hewitt-s-recordings-from-turkey-1974 the recordings are available] on the Net; his account of his meetings in 1974 has been published — ‘Encounterng Ubykh(s)’, in ''Arxeologija i ètnografija pontijsko-kavkazskogo regiona 5'', 195-204, 2016: Krasnodar; see also his ‘The labialised sibilants of Ubykh (North West Caucasian)’, in ''Revue des Etudes Géorgiennes et Caucasiennes, 2'', 1986, 21-30); the Abkhazian Viacheslav Chirikba, who has written on Ubykh settlements and [https://www.academia.edu/31381655/A_Dictionary_of_Ubykh_Personal_Names._-_Ubykh_Etudes._IV._Словарь_убыхских_личных_имен._-_Убыхские_этюды._IV Ubykh surnames]; the Turkish A. Sumru Özsoy.
Having an excellent memory and understanding quickly the goals of Dumézil and the other linguists who came to visit him, he was the primary source of not only the Ubykh language, but also of the [[mythology]], [[culture]] and customs of the [[Ubykh people]]. He spoke not only Ubykh, but also the [[Hakuchi Adyghe|Hakuchi]] dialect of [[Adyghe language|Adyghe]], allowing some comparative work to be done between these two members of the [[Northwest Caucasian languages|Northwest Caucasian]] family. He was also a fluent speaker of Turkish. He was a purist, and his [[idiolect]] of Ubykh was considered by Dumézil as the closest thing to a standard "literary" Ubykh language that existed.<ref name=TECW/> He is perhaps single-handedly responsible for the world's current knowledge of Ubykh being much more extensive and detailed than it would otherwise be.
Esenç died in 1992 at the age of 88. The inscription that he wanted on his gravestone read as follows:<ref name=TECW/>
{{Quote|''This is the grave of Tevfik Esenç. He was the last person able to speak the language they called Ubykh.''|Gravestone|inscription}}
In 1994, A. Sumru Özsoy organized an international conference, namely Conference on Northwest Caucasian Linguistics, at [[Boğaziçi University]] in memory of Dumézil and Esenç.<ref name="koe">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-SYou4fhWUgC&pg=PA33|title=First Person Singular III: Autobiographies by North American Scholars in the Language Sciences|author=E. F. K. Koerner|date=1 January 1998|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing|isbn=978-90-272-4576-2|page=33}}</ref>
